title: For Trade:  RARE Arisaka Type 99 Japanese WWII Rifle! Mum, bayonet, early run! +More
postcontent:
This was passed down through the family and ended up with me. I've spent hours upon hours researching the history of this rifle and believe it to be fairly rare considering it's condition as well as it's features. Probably not as rare as the sniper/scout model but if say it's up there! Would be a great addition to a WWII collection. I'll probay regret selling it but I'm sure it'll bring more joy to someone else. 

Japanese T99 Arisaka Rifle - Believed to be 3rd or 4th run by markings

- flawless, untouched chrysanthemum 
- nicely milled safety/release
- smooth teardrop shaped bolt lever
- 100% functioning anti-aircraft sights w/ collapsible wings
- un-bent monopod
- top half of the cleaning rod, needs extension
- wood is not cracked and really is in good condition. Better condition then some of my personal hunting rifles
- all matching serial numbers internally

Additional features

- bayonet, sheath and bayonet mount. The bayonet doesn't look to be from the same run as the rifle. To be honest it looks more like a last ditch bayonet, but I'm no expert. There are a few markings but they aren't as defined as the markings on the gun itself. The bayonet mount serial number doesn't match the serial numbers inside the gun. So it was probably added from another rifle somewhere along the line. 

- comes with dust cover. Doesn't have markings on it though. Not sure if it's original, late run, or a reproduction. 

- comes with a gun strap that is obviously not from WWII. 


Really a nice rifle. Would be happy to email more pictures of everything. Not sure what to ask price wise but feel free to offer. I'm open to trades and have a few boxes of 7.7 ammo that can be added for the right price/deal. This ammo isn't made any longer and runs up in the 80-125$ range per box when you can find it. 2 companies made it and I believe I have the better quality ammo of the two.

Statistically - 99% of attacks on individuals happen at a distance of 3 feet.

Do you practice blocking, moving off the ‘X’, drawing from concealment, point shooting, working through malfunctions, let alone fighting to get to your sidearm - all simultaneously… or do your training drills consist of shooting a non-reactive target at a fixed distance? If you fall into the second category – you’re not alone; most shooters in Florida who are licensed to carry concealed never practice advanced tactics, let alone drills which prepare them for a telephone booth sized fight for their life!

This one-on-one course deals with what happens in real-time at “bad breath distances” when an encounter transitions from conversation to your adversary striking you with the clear intent of taking you to the ground and having their way with you.

It is as much a thinking course as it is a shooting skills course taught by an instructor who was a Special Forces soldier for 8 years and a high risk bodyguard in 13 countries for more than 20 years.

Being one-on-one allows the instructor to cater the course to your specific daily activities: sitting behind a desk, working from a vehicle, a mother with small children, etc. - instead of a cookie-cutter curriculum. We maximize your time with us so you get the most increase in your skills possible.

This course is taught only during the week as public ranges are swamped to capacity during weekend hours and the advanced drills you will be practicing are not permitted without an instructor. The course locations are restricted to West Palm Beach & Fort Lauderdale/Pembroke.

Cost for this dynamic course is $250. (plus range fee) for 3 hours of immersion-style one-on-one training.

Course requirements: Concealed weapon permit, pistol(semi-auto or revolver), concealment holster (if you purse carry the instructor will provide several purses for you to shoot through), 2 working magazines or speed loaders and a holster/pouch for same, 150 rounds of ball ammunition, eye & ear protection.

Please call REDACTED to make your reservation.

Mint, unissued special production Smith & Wesson M-681-3 stainless steel square butt revolver made in .38 Special caliber for the ConRail railroad Police Department in 1989. Rollmarked "C.R.P.D" above the left side trigger guard.

This is one of only 465 681s that S&W made for the railroad in .38 Special instead of .357 Magnum as a special order through Pennsylvania Police Supply (now "Officer Store") in Chalk Hill, Pa. in 1989. ConRail began switching to automatic pistols for their railway cops around 1990 and some of the revolvers were never issued and eventually made their way into private hands.

Perfect condition, with original box that reads 'Special' under Features on the label, manual, oil paper and plug.

title: For Sale:  Mathews Helim AKA Heli-m $1199 OR BEST OFFER! LOTS OF EXTRAS!
location: North of Green Bay (Pulaski), Green Bay, Wisconsin
postcontent:
For sale is a Mathews Helim bow. I bought it brand new from the factory for $995 1 year ago. I was never a Mathews fan, but this bow draws back very smoothly, is fast, and is very accurate, so I bought it. It has a 29 inch draw length and is capable of going up to 70lbs. I have it set for 65 pounds right now. If you have a different draw length, any Mathews dealer will adjust the draw for you free of charge.

I didn’t skip any corners when I put accessories on the bow. It is equipped with a HHA adjustable pin sight ($150) All the yardage makers are right on up to 60 yards (furthest I ever shot) The sight pin is 0.010” it was the finest sight they had, so you will have no problem shooting at long distances. It has a Quality Archery Designs HDX drop away rest ($130) It comes with 6 carbon express maxima arrows ($80) that are camouflage, and 3 rage broad heads (2 blade version $40) It also comes with a hard case ($40) a TruFire 4 finger relase ($100) a Primos bow sling ($30) a block target ($80) and a black hole target. 

I have a lot of money stuck into this setup, I realize that this is a year old and its is used, but I can honestly say its been shot very little. I dialed it in right away last year and didn’t use it. This year I shot it 2 arrows at 20 yards and 2 arrows at 40 yards, and it was right on. This thing is so accurate I robin hooded an arrow at 40 yards. I cannot shoot more than 2 times at 1 target. I went out and shot 3 deer this year with it (all pass throughs and did not run far) I’m selling it because I’m moving to California for awhile and wont be using it for a few years.

Any questions, or if you would like to see this amazing bow, feel free to call or text Mike at REDACTED. I work 6am till 3pm usually, so if I don't answer your call or text right away, I will get back to you. Thank you for looking!
